# Custom In-House AI Voice Bot Implementation Plan

This document outlines the technical architecture and implementation strategy for building a highly scalable, rock-solid AI Voice Bot backend completely **in-house**. This system relies 100% on open-source models running on your own servers, ensuring zero external API dependencies, maximum privacy, and complete customization for your Vicidial/Asterisk integration.

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Please review the updated **In-House Technology Stack**. Because we are self-hosting everything, achieving ultra-low latency requires efficient model serving. We have selected the fastest, most lightweight open-source models available. Let me know if you are ready to approve this so we can begin building.

---

## 1. Architecture Overview

The backend is an **event-driven WebSocket server** that acts as the central orchestrator. It streams audio to and from Asterisk, passing it through local AI inference engines.

### The Real-Time Pipeline:
1. **Audio Ingestion:** Asterisk streams raw audio (PCMU 8000Hz) to the Python WebSocket server.
2. **Local STT (Speech-to-Text):** The audio stream is chunked and transcribed locally in real-time.
3. **Local LLM (Logic):** The text is fed into a locally hosted language model to determine if the lead is qualified.
4. **Local TTS (Text-to-Speech):** The LLM's response is converted to audio by a local, ultra-fast TTS engine.
5. **Audio Output:** Audio is streamed back to Asterisk.
6. **Action Execution:** The bot triggers an Asterisk AMI/AGI command to transfer the call to an agent or drop it.

---

## 2. 100% Open-Source Technology Stack

To meet your requirements of being lightweight, extremely powerful, and self-hosted with high concurrency, we will use the following tools:

### Core Orchestrator
*   **Language & Framework:** **Python with FastAPI**. Highly asynchronous, perfect for handling hundreds of concurrent WebSockets efficiently.
*   **Audio Processing:** `numpy` and standard Python audio libraries for handling fast memory buffering.

### Self-Hosted AI Inference (The "Brain" & Voice)
*   **Speech-to-Text (STT):** **Faster-Whisper**. 
    *   *Why:* It uses CTranslate2, making it up to 4x faster than standard OpenAI Whisper while using significantly less memory. It can stream transcriptions locally with very low latency.
*   **Language Model (LLM):** **vLLM hosting Llama-3-8B-Instruct** (or Phi-3-Mini).
    *   *Why:* vLLM is a high-throughput, memory-efficient serving engine. Running a small, quantized model like Llama-3-8B ensures blazing-fast responses and minimal resource hogging, leaving room for hundreds of concurrent calls.
*   **Text-to-Speech (TTS):** **Piper TTS**.
    *   *Why:* Piper is designed specifically for ultra-fast, local voice generation (originally for Raspberry Pi/Edge devices). It generates audio faster than real-time on CPU, meaning it scales incredibly well on powerful servers without needing massive GPU clusters.

---

## 3. Step-by-Step Implementation Strategy

We will build this iteratively, ensuring each component is lightweight and fast before moving to the next.

### Phase 1: The Core Async Server
*   Setup a FastAPI project structure.
*   Implement the WebSocket endpoint to receive and send audio chunks asynchronously.
*   Build the audio buffering mechanism.

### Phase 2: Local AI Model Integration
*   Integrate Faster-Whisper for real-time local transcription of the audio buffer.
*   Integrate Piper TTS locally to convert text back into raw audio streams.
*   *Verification:* Speak into a test client, see the text, and hear Piper speak a hardcoded response instantly.

### Phase 3: The Conversational Brain
*   Connect the orchestrator to your local vLLM instance.
*   Implement strict system prompting (e.g., "Ask if they are over 65. Output [TRANSFER] if yes, [DROP] if no").
*   Implement conversation state management (remembering what was said during the call).

### Phase 4: Integration Prep & Load Testing
*   Expose endpoints for campaign management (setting different prompts for different campaigns).
*   Create a simulated multi-call test to benchmark CPU/GPU usage with your local hardware.

---

## 4. Integration with Asterisk/Vicidial

Once the standalone bot is fast and stable:
1.  **Audio Link:** Use Asterisk `AudioSocket` or `EAGI` to forward SIP audio to our FastAPI server.
2.  **Transfers:** The bot will utilize the Asterisk Manager Interface (AMI) via a Python library like `panoramisk` to execute Dial/Transfer commands to your agent queues when a lead is qualified.

## Verification & Mocking (Testing Without a Dialer)

Since you do not have access to the dialers right now, we will build a **Mock Dialer** ecosystem alongside the bot. This allows you to verify the bot's logic, latency, and voice quality end-to-end, and provides a working reference for the team doing the final Asterisk integration.

### 1. The Python Mock Dialer (`mock_dialer.py`)
We will create a standalone Python script that mimics exactly what Asterisk will do. 
*   **How it works:** You run the script in your terminal. It will connect to the bot's WebSocket server, capture your computer's microphone, convert your voice to the telecom standard (8000Hz, u-law), and stream it to the bot. It will simultaneously receive the bot's audio and play it through your speakers.
*   **Why this is useful:** The integration team can literally look at the code inside `mock_dialer.py` to see exactly what binary formats and JSON payloads the Asterisk server needs to send to the bot.

### 2. Browser-Based Testing Interface
We will include a lightweight HTML/JavaScript page hosted directly by the FastAPI server.
*   **How it works:** You open `http://localhost:8000/test` in your browser. You click "Start Call", and speak into your browser. The browser streams the audio to the backend via WebSockets.
*   **Why this is useful:** This gives non-technical stakeholders (or you) an easy visual interface to chat with the bot, see the live text transcription, and see the exact moment the bot decides to output a `[TRANSFER]` or `[DROP]` command without installing any software.

### 3. Automated Audio File Streaming
For load testing and automated checks, we will create a script that takes a pre-recorded `.wav` file (e.g., an audio recording of a customer saying "I am 68 years old") and streams it to the server to verify the bot always replies correctly and issues the transfer command.

**If this entire plan and the mock testing strategy look good to you, please give the approval and we will begin building the core components!**
